Question: Android view enum: :In Android I want to make a enum with views (let's say with EditTexts).I thought to initialize an EditText with findViewById(R.id.something), you have to do that in a activity-class or you need a instance of this class.So how can I initialize the EditTexts in a enum or can I set the Views from the main-class?I thought about something like this, but it won't work:enum Edits {    one(/* what to write here */), two(/* what to write here */);    private EditText editText;    Edits(EditText editText){        this.editText = editText;    }    EditText getEditText(){        return this.editText;    }    void setEditText(EditText editText){ // Maybe something like this?        this.editText = editText;    }}So, how would you do that?
Please using this api: Activity.findViewById.
Answer: $CODE:
```java
public enum Edits {
    one, two;

    private EditText editText;

    void setEditText(EditText editText){
        this.editText = editText;
    }

    EditText getEditText(){
        return this.editText;
    }
}
```
In your activity, you can set the EditTexts like this:
```java
Edits.one.setEditText((EditText) findViewById(R.id.one));
Edits.two.setEditText((EditText) findViewById(R.id.two));
```
$EXPLANATION:
In this solution, we define an enum Edits with two EditText fields one and two. We also define a method setEditText() to set the EditText for each enum constant and a method getEditText() to get the EditText for each enum constant.

In the activity, we use the findViewById() method to get the EditText views by their ids (R.id.one and R.id.two) and set them to the corresponding enum constants.

Then, we can get the EditText views by calling the getEditText() method on the enum constants. For example, Edits.one.getEditText() will return the EditText view for the one constant.

This way, we can initialize the EditText views in the activity and use them in the enum without having to pass the activity instance around.

Please note that we need to cast the result of findViewById() to EditText because findViewById() returns a View and we are assigning it to an EditText.

Also, remember to replace R.id.one and R.id.two with the actual ids of your EditText views in your layout file.
